<HEADLINE>
PRO-INDEPENDENCE GROUP TO PROMOTE CAUSE VIA ONLINE COLLEGE
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  Jan.  19  (CNA) 01/19/07  19:30:40 (By Lilian Wu)
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan Association of University Professors (TAUP) said
Friday that it will organize an online college to strengthen
consciousness of the idea that Taiwan has a separate identity
from China and to firm the resolve of the Taiwan people to
establish a nation.
</P>
<P>
TAUP Chairman Tsay Ting-kuei made the remarks at a fundraising
lunch that also gathered legislators from the ruling Democratic
Progressive Party (DPP) and its ally the Taiwan Solidarity Union,
as well as from the main opposition Kuomintang (KMT).
</P>
<P>
Tsay said the school will recruit people over 16 who identify
themselves with Taiwan and that the college's board of directors
will be devoted to its development and offering counseling
services.
</P>
<P>
The college will have one president and four vice presidents.
There will be five colleges in pre-college, arts and letters,
politics and socio-economics, science and engineering as well
special studies.
</P>
<P>
The college will serve as an educational institute based on the
principles of "Taiwan, by Taiwan and for Taiwan, " he said. It
will pool resources at home and overseas for online teaching.
</P>
<P>
"To realize the idea of Taiwan's independent sovereignty and the
establishment of the country of Taiwan, The TAUP is very willing
to take on the responsibility," he said.
</P>
<P>
DPP lawmakers Trong Chai, You Ching, Jao Yung-ching, William La
i, Huang Wei- cher, Chang Chun-hsiung, Winston Dang, Kao Chien-
chih, Winston Dang, TSU Legislator George K. Liu and KMT
Legislator Lo Ming-tsai attended the lunch.
</P>
